{
  "texts": [
    "With the use of a differentiable ray-marching process from a collection of posed RGB photos, it is possible to learn the underlying voxel structures.",
    "Voxels without scene-related content are skipped.",
    "Compared to NeRF, it is 10 times faster.",
    "NeRF rendered each pixel using a single ray, which frequently resulted in blurring or aliasing at different resolutions.",
    "Mip-NeRF, described in (Jonathan et al. 2021), renders each pixel using a conical frustum rather than a ray, which lessens aliasing, enables the display of fine details in an image, and lowers error rates by between 17 and 60%."
  ]
}